Iris flower image with the R code

The sepal is a part of a flower that is typically green and leaf-like. It forms the outter layer of the flower and protects the buds as they develop before it opens. The petal, on the other hand, is the colorful part of the flower pollinators such as bees, birds, butterflies et cetera.

Iris Table Summary with the R Code 

#Loading the libraries needed to run the date

library(knitr)

data("iris")
summary_table <- summary(iris) %>% 
  as.matrix() %>% 
  as.data.frame()

#adding a column for the lables (min, max, etc)
summary_table <- tibble::rownames_to_column(summary_table, var = "Statistic")

#create the Flextable
flex_table <- flextable(summary_table)

#Add style to the table
flex_table <- flex_table %>% 
  set_header_labels(values = list(Statistic = "Summary Statistic")) %>% 
  autofit()

The table provides a statistical summary of the Iris Plant dataset such as the minimum, maximum, mean, median and 1st and 3rd Quartiles for each sepal and petal measurement.

  1. Mean: The mean tells you that the typical size of the petal is on average. It gives a sense of what the flowers look like in terms of the size of their petals.

  2. Standard Deviation: This tells how much the petal sizes vary from the average petal size. If the variation is small, that tells us that the flowers have petals that are smaller in size. If the variation is large, it tells us that there are a wide range of petal sizes.

  3. Understanding the range of sizes (Min, 1st Quartile, Median, 3rd Quartile, Max): These break down the petal sizes further.

  • The minimum tells us the smallest petal size, and the maximum tells us the largest.
  • The median is the middle petal size, giving us an idea of the flower if you line them up from the smallest to the largest. The middle petal size would be what a typical flower petal would look like.
  • The quartiles This tells the spread of the sizes. 25% of the flowers have smaller petals then the first quartile, and 75% are smaller than the third quartile. This helps in the distribution of the petals.

Key Takeaway


This analysis highlights common petal sizes, their variations, and any unusual patterns across three iris species Setosa, Versicolor and Virginica based on fifty observations per species.


The dataset looked at three flower species (Setosa, Versicolor and Virginica) and performed 50 observation for each plant species.

Visualizing the Data

Scatter Plot of Sepal Length vs Sepal Width

library(ggplot2)

#Custom color palette

custom_colors <- c("setosa" = "purple", "versicolor" = "orange", "virginica" = "green")
my_plot <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species))+
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  labs(title = "Sepal Length vs Sepal Width by Species",
       x= "Sepal Length (cm)",
       y= "Sepal Width (cm)") +
  scale_color_manual(values = custom_colors) +
theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
      panel.background = element_blank()) +
        theme_classic()

## View the plot 
print(my_plot)

Chart Observations

An observation of the scatter plot shows the Setosa species as a wider sepal width compared to Virginica and versicolor. However, there are some virginica that differ in length and width to versicolor but for the most part they have similar length and width.

Scatter Plot of Petal Length vs Petal Width

custom_colors <- c("setosa" = "purple", "versicolor" = "orange", "virginica" = "green")

my_plot_2 <-ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, y = Petal.Width, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +

       x = "Petal Length (cm)",
       y = "Petal Width (cm)") +

      panel.background = element_blank()) +
  theme_classic()

## View the plot 
print(my_plot_2)

Chart Observations

Here we observe the comparison of petal length and width. Setosa caught my attention firstits clearly separate from the others, sitting close to the bottom of the plot with shorter petals that are also narrower. Setosa are of a smaller side in both length and width.

Then theres Versicolor and Virginica, which are much more similar in size and sit closer together on the plot. I noticed that Versicolors petals were in the middle of the graph, but Virginica stands out a bit more by going up higheralmost like a taller sibling. What struck me about Virginica was how its petals tend to spread wider, even though the overall length isnt too different from Versicolor. The few data points that branch off to the other side of the y-axis made me think theres a little more variability in the petal width here.

What really stood out for me, though, was the contrast in sepal length. While Versicolor and Virginica have similar petal sizes, Virginicas sepals are clearly longer, making it stand apart from Versicolor, which was more in the middle range.

Box plot for Sepal Length by Species

custom_colors <- c("setosa" = "purple", "versicolor" = "orange", "virginica" = "green")

my_plot_3 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
   labs(title = "Distribution of Sepal Length by Species",
  x = "Species",
  y = "Sepal Length (cm)") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors) +
  theme_classic()

## View the plot 
print(my_plot_3)

#### Chart Observation

The box plot pattern observed looks like a step-like pattern. This suggests that Setosa species have the shortest sepals.Versicolor species have an intermediate length sepal and Virginica species have the longest sepals.

Outliers: There is one outlier present in the data set for Virginica. This means that there is a data point for the Virginica species that falls outside the expected range. It could be a unique case that represent a very long or very short sepal length in the species. The sepal length could mean longer sepal may offer better protection to the flower buds. Species with smaller sepals may not suggest it does not require protection and grow in environments where there are fewer threats and so the sepal length is standard.

While Setosas distance indicates it is distinctly separate in petal length than the other two species.

Virginica does not have an outlier which could indicate that the length and petals are consistent with this species. The longer whiskers could indicate that at the upper part of the species the petals could have a wider lengths.

Histogram Chart of Sepal Length by Species

custom_colors <- c("setosa" = "purple", "versicolor" = "orange", "virginica" = "green")
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.8, position = "dodge", alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Sepal Length by Species",
       x = "Sepal Length (cm)",
       y = "Frequency") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)+
  theme_classic()

Chart Observations

Note Using the Dodge in the code makes the histogram charts look more like a column chart or bar chart than a histogram. It was used to separate the bars for the species. Here is a example of what the chart would look like below without the Dodge code added.

The isolated Setosa bar suggests that there is an instance or an outlier and this sepal length is distinct from the other species and also for an observation for Virginica. You can also see that the Versicolor and Virginica sepals are similar to each other and more spreadout than Setosa.It can also imply that they overlap in some areas of their data points.

Chart Observations

The observation of the chart shows a low bar for Setosa this could be that some of the Setosa species have narrow septals. At the far end their is a lone Virginica bar this could imply that there are outliers in the septals of the Virginica species.

All three species grouped together may indicate where the data for the species overlap.The very tall Setosa bar indicates it may have the highest frequency in the data set. Another Setosa bar along the X-axis which is shorter than the other species could indicate there are less Setosa with wider sepal widths.

Working with the Iris dataset has deepened my understanding of data visualization and R. I learned how to use ggplot2 for creating intuitive, customizable plots, and how code like geom_histogram() can be tailored with options like position = "dodge". This allowed me to create more informative, clear visualizations that helped in interpreting patterns and distributions.

I also learned about the importance of experimenting with different visual formats and how subtle changes in the code (like adjusting binwidth or alpha) can significantly affect the readability and insights derived from the data.

Exploring this dataset also taught me about understanding data structure and the importance of considering both statistical patterns and visualization aesthetics to communicate insights effectively.

Overall, this project gave me a solid foundation in R and provided valuable practice with interpreting data through the lens of visualization.
